Our design system team renamed <Card> to <Panel> across 340 files on a Thursday afternoon without warning anyone, because apparently that's just how that team operates. I found out when the build broke at 6pm and I had a dentist appointment the next morning I did not want to spend prepping for. Normally this is a find and replace nightmare spread across three repos, half a dozen import styles, and at least one file where somebody aliased the import as CardComponent for reasons lost to git blame.
Instead of doing it by hand, I pointed Codemod’s AI powered generator at the diff and asked it to write the transform. It didn’t get it right the first time. It got it right on the fourth try, after I fed it two failing test cases. That’s the part worth talking about, because “AI writes your refactor” sounds like magic until you actually watch it work, and the real story is messier and more useful than the pitch.
Why Hand Rolled Find and Replace Stops Working
Simple renames are fine with sed or a regex. The moment you need to understand the AST, meaning you care about whether something is a JSX attribute versus a plain object property, or whether an import is a default versus named export, regex starts lying to you. It’ll happily rename a variable called Card that has nothing to do with your component, or miss a re-export three files deep.
That’s what jscodeshift and ts-morph exist for. Both let you parse code into an actual syntax tree and manipulate nodes instead of guessing at text patterns. jscodeshift has been the default for JS codemods for years (Facebook built it for exactly this kind of large migration). ts-morph is the newer, friendlier option if your codebase leans hard into TypeScript, since it understands types, not just syntax shape.
Here’s a hand written ts-morph script for the rename, which is roughly what I expected to spend my evening writing:
import { Project, SyntaxKind } from "ts-morph";const project = new Project({
tsConfigFilePath: "./tsconfig.json",
});const sourceFiles = project.getSourceFiles("src/**/*.tsx");for (const file of sourceFiles) {
const importDecls = file.getImportDeclarations(); for (const decl of importDecls) {
if (decl.getModuleSpecifierValue().endsWith("/Card")) {
decl.setModuleSpecifier(
decl.getModuleSpecifierValue().replace("/Card", "/Panel")
); decl.getNamedImports().forEach((named) => {
if (named.getName() === "Card") {
named.setName("Panel");
}
});
}
} file.getDescendantsOfKind(SyntaxKind.JsxOpeningElement).forEach((el) => {
if (el.getTagNameNode().getText() === "Card") {
el.getTagNameNode().replaceWithText("Panel");
}
});
}project.saveSync();That’s a solid start but it misses closing tags, self closing elements, and any aliased import. Writing the full version by hand is maybe 45 minutes of tedious edge case chasing, and that’s for a rename, the easy end of codemod difficulty.
Where the AI Part Actually Helped
What I did instead: gave Codemod’s generator the before and after snippet from two files the design team had already hand migrated, plus a plain English description of the intent (“rename Card to Panel everywhere, including aliased imports and JSX self closing tags, preserve prop order”). First attempt handled the import rename fine and completely ignored self closing JSX tags. Second attempt fixed that and broke the aliased import case. By the fourth pass, after I added a failing test file specifically for the alias scenario, it produced something close to what I’d written above but with the edge cases actually covered, including a case I hadn’t thought of: a barrel file re-exporting Card under yet another name.
The number that stuck with me from digging into how these tools measure themselves: iterative refinement on generated codemods took accuracy from around 26 percent on a first pass to 54 percent after four rounds. That’s not “AI nails it instantly,” that’s “AI gets you a rough draft and you still need to drive.” Which, honestly, tracks with basically every other AI coding tool I’ve used this year. The value isn’t zero shot correctness, it’s compressing 45 minutes of tedious AST fiddling into ten minutes of reviewing and correcting a draft.
Running It Safely Across Three Repos
The actual rollout mattered more than the codemod itself. I ran it dry first with a diff preview, checked it against a sampling of files by hand (maybe 15 out of 340, picked somewhat randomly plus every file that looked structurally weird), then ran it for real behind a feature branch with CI gating the merge. jscodeshift supports running transforms in parallel across worker processes, which matters once you're past a few hundred files and don't want to wait around.
npx jscodeshift -t rename-card-to-panel.js src/ --parser=tsx --extensions=tsx,tsOne thing that bit me: the codemod happily rewrote a test fixture file that intentionally used the old Card name to test backward compatibility. Nothing in the AST told it "this one's supposed to stay old." That's on me for not excluding the fixtures directory up front, not on the tool. AST tools do exactly what you tell them, they just don't know what you meant.
What I’d Tell Someone About to Try This
Start smaller than you think you need to. My first instinct was to point the generator at the whole 340 file diff and ask for one giant transform. That produced something confidently wrong, because the model was pattern matching across files that had actually diverged in subtle ways (some had the alias, some didn’t, one file had a completely unrelated local variable also named Card). Breaking it into three smaller transforms, one for imports, one for JSX elements, one for the barrel file re-export, made each piece small enough to actually review line by line. Composition beats one giant clever script, same as it does in the code you're refactoring in the first place.
Keep a scratch repo around for testing transforms before you run them against anything real. I cloned a throwaway copy of our monorepo, ran the generated transform there first, and diffed the output against what I expected by hand for a dozen representative files. Cost me twenty minutes. Saved me from shipping a transform that would’ve silently broken the fixtures directory in the real repo, since I caught that mistake in the sandbox instead.
The Part Nobody Puts in the Marketing Copy
Codemods, AI assisted or not, are still a “know what you’re doing” tool. If you can’t read the generated transform and explain why each node manipulation is correct, you shouldn’t be running it against 340 files unsupervised. The AI made the first draft faster. It did not make understanding ASTs optional, and I don’t think it’s going to for a while.
Was it faster than doing it by hand? Yes, probably by half. Was it faster than just asking the design system team to give a two week deprecation window before renaming things? Also yes, but that ship had sailed by the time I found out, so here we are.
I made the dentist appointment, for what it’s worth. Barely.
